WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.130 --> 00:00:03.420
Hal Varian: Okay, I'm Hal Varian.
I'm the chief economist here at Google, and

00:00:03.420 --> 00:00:09.700
it's my pleasure to introduce Yoram Bauman.
He claims to be the world's only "stand-up

00:00:09.700 --> 00:00:12.660
economist."
And I thought, "Gee, there's a chance for

00:00:12.660 --> 00:00:17.039
entry here.
I could maybe try this myself."

00:00:17.039 --> 00:00:21.560
And when Ann told me to do the introduction,
I said, "Is that really fair?" because after

00:00:21.560 --> 00:00:28.529
all, I'm a really tough act to follow. [laughter]
But despite this, you know, I said, "Okay,

00:00:28.529 --> 00:00:32.320
I'll give it a try."
And, "What's so hard about being a stand-up

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:34.080
economist?
After all, you just go to Google; you type

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:39.070
in 'economics jokes.'" So I tried that.
And then, a few minutes later, I typed in

00:00:39.070 --> 00:00:45.170
"funny economics jokes." [laughter]
And then, I tried "funny economics jokes I

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:47.640
haven't heard."
And you know, it just goes on.

00:00:47.640 --> 00:00:51.610
I realize there was more to it than really
met the naked eye.

00:00:51.610 --> 00:00:56.510
But I did come up with a story that I want
to use to introduce him.

00:00:56.510 --> 00:01:01.600
I'm not sure if this specifically applies
to economists, but at least it's a nice academic

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:05.530
story.
It's about the full professor and the associate

00:01:05.530 --> 00:01:11.749
professor who are holding a debate about what
fraction of sex is fun and what fraction is

00:01:11.749 --> 00:01:16.060
work.
So the full professor says, "75 percent work.

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:19.590
25 percent fun."
And the associate professor says, "No. It's

00:01:19.590 --> 00:01:23.460
50/50."
So they're arguing, they're getting citations,

00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:26.569
they're Googling things -- and an assistant
professor comes by.

00:01:26.569 --> 00:01:32.219
They ask his opinion.
He says, "Well, I think it's 75 fun and 25

00:01:32.219 --> 00:01:35.100
percent work."
So they argue along for awhile.

00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:38.969
Finally, a research assistant comes by.
They say, "What's your opinion?"

00:01:38.969 --> 00:01:41.270
The research assistant says, "This is totally
obvious.

00:01:41.270 --> 00:01:45.630
It's obvious. It's 100 percent fun."
He said, "How could you be so sure?"

00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:51.889
He said, "Well, if there were any work involved,
they'd make us do it." [laughter]

00:01:51.889 --> 00:01:58.119
So, with that, I would like to introduce -- not
the assistant professor, not the associate

00:01:58.119 --> 00:02:03.880
professor, not the full professor -- the dean
of economic comedy -- Yoram Bauman.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:06.340
&gt;&gt; [Applause]

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:17.160
Yoram Bauman: Thank you for that lovely introduction.
The setup was a bit long, but the punch line

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:20.390
was good.
I should -- before I forget, I should show

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:26.480
you my T-shirt. [laughter]
It says, "Stimulate the economy. Buy me a

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:29.970
drink."
I used to wear one that said, "Enjoy capitalism,"

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:35.120
sort of in the Coca-Cola lettering.
But, as long as unemployment is above whatever

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:37.550
 -- 9 percent -- I think that that one's in
the closet.

00:02:37.550 --> 00:02:43.980
I also forget to tell people, "Here's a joke
that I'm really proud of," because it's not

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:45.940
very often that you can make up a knock-knock
joke.

00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:49.110
But I made up a knock-knock joke.
It's an economics knock-knock joke that's

00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:52.030
sweeping England.
So I have to put on my terrible British accent.

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:53.030
Ready? Here we go.

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:54.210
Q [Imitating a British accent] Knock knock.

00:02:54.210 --> 00:02:55.210
A Who's there?

00:02:55.210 --> 00:02:56.210
Q Economist.

00:02:56.210 --> 00:02:57.210
A Economist who?

00:02:57.210 --> 00:02:59.230
Q Ei cah na missed the financial crisis, but
I promise I'll do better next time.

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:04.961
[laughter]
And the great thing about that joke is that

00:03:04.961 --> 00:03:07.320
I'll be able to keep telling that forever,
right?

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:11.640
Because whatever happens in the world economy,
you can be pretty sure that, as an economist,

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:15.120
I'll be able to say that "Ei cah na missed
it," right?

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:18.110
Anyway, so it's a pleasure to be here with
all of you today.

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:23.370
And, in Hal's honor, I thought I would start
with a piece called, "What to Expect When

00:03:23.370 --> 00:03:29.070
You're Expecting the Nobel Prize." [laughter]
So for any of you that are -- well, first

00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:32.560
of all, I should say that I also teach part-time
at a high school in Seattle.

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:36.080
And I share this with my high school students.
And I said, "Do you guys get the joke?"

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:40.150
And one of them said, "Isn't there like a
baby book called 'What to Expect When You're

00:03:40.150 --> 00:03:42.200
Expecting?'"
And I was like, "Yeah, that's very good. How

00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:46.210
did you know that?"
And he said, "I saw it in the movie 'Knocked

00:03:46.210 --> 00:03:52.030
Up.'" [laughter]
So that's how education happens these days,

00:03:52.030 --> 00:03:55.850
I guess.
So this is "What to Expect When You're Expecting

00:03:55.850 --> 00:03:57.840
the Nobel Prize."
So, first of all, you should expect an early

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:02.490
morning phone call from a long-dead economist.
So, when you win the Nobel Prize -- just in

00:04:02.490 --> 00:04:06.350
case you're getting ready for that -- they
call you up at a reasonable hour Sweden time

00:04:06.350 --> 00:04:10.860
I guess, but it's 6:00 in the morning East
Coast time -- 3:00 in the morning West Coast

00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:12.720
time -- when they tell you that you won the
Nobel Prize.

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:16.380
And then, a fellow calls up from the Nobel
Prize website and does an interview with you

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:20.709
that they record and transcribe and then post
on their website.

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:23.790
So here's some snippets from the Nobel Prize
interview.

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:26.910
So, the first one is with Edmund Phelps in
2006.

00:04:26.910 --> 00:04:31.470
And the interview is conducted by the editor
in chief of NobelPrize.org, whose name you'll

00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:34.490
see in a moment.
So here's the interview, "Hello, may I speak

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:37.600
to Professor Phelps, please?"
And he says, "Who's calling?"

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:41.600
And the response is, "I'm from the Nobel Foundation,
and my name is Adam Smith."

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:53.820
[laughter]
And Edmund Phelps says, "Ha ha ha."

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:57.340
And then, Adam Smith says, "I know it could
be a hoax call with a name like that.

00:04:57.340 --> 00:05:04.960
It's a terrible burden I carry." [laughter]
So, one of the things that you see from these

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:10.150
transcripts of these interviews with the Nobel
Prize winners is part of what I think US Weekly

00:05:10.150 --> 00:05:14.560
should start running a segment called, "Nobel
Prize winners: They're just like us."

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:18.230
So here's more from Edmund Phelps.
The question comes in, "How are you going

00:05:18.230 --> 00:05:21.870
to celebrate winning the Nobel Prize?" Right?
And he says, "Well, right now I'm thinking

00:05:21.870 --> 00:05:26.490
about breakfast." [laughter]
And Adam Smith says, "Yeah, I bet it's got

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:30.340
to be a 2-egg day at least."
And then, Edmund Phelps starts talking about

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:33.230
cholesterol.
Here, Edmund's scared of cholesterol for a

00:05:33.230 --> 00:05:35.960
long time.
But I understand the white of the egg is quite

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:38.170
safe.
I'll ask my wife whether perchance she has

00:05:38.170 --> 00:05:45.370
an egg in the house.
One of the funniest exchanges in the transcripts

00:05:45.370 --> 00:05:49.190
comes from Leonid Hurwicz, who's the oldest
person to win a Nobel Prize in any field.

00:05:49.190 --> 00:05:55.449
So he and his wife Evelyn -- and this is their
phone call from October 2007.

00:05:55.449 --> 00:05:57.690
So, the phone call comes in, "Good morning,
Professor Hurwicz."

00:05:57.690 --> 00:06:02.139
And he says, "Hello?"
And the other end says -- and his wife says,

00:06:02.139 --> 00:06:06.980
"He's hard-of-hearing." [laughter]
And the Nobel Prize dialer says, "I'm sorry,

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:09.030
I'll speak louder.
Can you hear me now?"

00:06:09.030 --> 00:06:16.480
And his wife says, "Yes." [laughter]
And then, "Thank you. My name is Adam Smith."

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:27.370
And awghh! [Laughter]
So, these transcripts are actually quite funny.

00:06:27.370 --> 00:06:30.650
And one of the things that they used to do
that they no longer do -- they used to ask

00:06:30.650 --> 00:06:34.650
the Nobel Prize winner to explain in simple
layperson's terms what they won the Nobel

00:06:34.650 --> 00:06:38.320
Prize for.
And they no longer ask them that question.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:41.121
And instead what they do is, they tell them
what they won the Nobel Prize for.

00:06:41.121 --> 00:06:45.961
And then, they say, "Is that right?" [laughter]
So then, all the Nobel Prize winner has to

00:06:45.961 --> 00:06:50.040
do is say "yes."
And it actually is -- like, one of the challenges

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:53.389
there is really explaining, I think, your
research in real simple terms.

00:06:53.389 --> 00:06:58.020
And so, I'm here promoting this book, "The
Cartoon Introduction to Economics," which

00:06:58.020 --> 00:07:03.370
is a super fun book.
Really, it was really fun to work on the book

00:07:03.370 --> 00:07:07.419
with Grady Klein, who's not an economist,
but he now knows a fair amount about economics

00:07:07.419 --> 00:07:11.210
and is a terrific illustrator.
It was a neat format -- kind of "graphic nonfiction."

00:07:11.210 --> 00:07:16.210
And one of the fun pieces that we have throughout
the book are these cartoons about "Congratulations,

00:07:16.210 --> 00:07:21.460
You Win the Nobel Prize." So here's Jim Tobin
saying, "Don't put all your eggs in one basket."

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:23.960
And the king of Sweden says, "Congratulations,
you win the Nobel Prize."

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:27.770
And this was actually based on a true story.
And this was the impetus for this line of

00:07:27.770 --> 00:07:32.370
jokes, because his obituary in the New York
Times told the story about how, when he went

00:07:32.370 --> 00:07:38.010
to accept the Nobel Prize and went to give
his -- at the press conference, the reporter

00:07:38.010 --> 00:07:40.270
said, "Well, you know, explain what you won
the Nobel Prize for."

00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:43.860
And he did it for Portfolio Selection Theory,
which is about investment stuff.

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:45.669
And he said, "Well, like there's alpha and
there's beta."

00:07:45.669 --> 00:07:47.770
And the reporters were like, "No, no, no -- that's
too hard," right?

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:50.229
"Make it simple."
And he said, "Well, it's kind of like 'Don't

00:07:50.229 --> 00:07:53.210
put all your eggs in one basket.'"
And then, headlines around the world the next

00:07:53.210 --> 00:07:59.210
day said, "Economist wins Nobel Prize for
'Don't Put All Your Eggs in One Basket." [laughter]

00:07:59.210 --> 00:08:02.040
So this is a true story, and it was the impetus
for the other jokes that we have on this.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:06.870
So here's John Nash who won for Game Theory,
who's figured out the optimal strategy for

00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:12.870
"Rock, Paper, Scissors."
George Akerlof, who won for "Adverse Selection,"

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:17.150
which is related to individual health insurance
markets, saying, "Buying an individual health

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:20.230
insurance policy can be a real pain in the
neck."

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:24.789
Joseph Stiglitz "Sometimes the Invisible Hand
is Invisible Because It's Not There." [laughter]

00:08:24.789 --> 00:08:26.780
 -- which is actually a classic Joseph Stiglitz
line.

00:08:26.780 --> 00:08:30.690
Daniel Kahneman, "Human beings are not always
rational."

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:35.020
And so, he's actually a psychologist who won
the Nobel Prize in economics for sort of his

00:08:35.020 --> 00:08:38.890
pioneering work in behavioral economics and
looking at, you know, "When do people really

00:08:38.890 --> 00:08:43.770
fulfill sort of the rational model that economists
sometimes use?"

00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:47.200
So, those are some of the cool panels from
the cartoon book.

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:52.440
And then, here's one -- I think -- my prediction
is that Marty Weitzman from Harvard is going

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:55.360
to win one of these days for his work on environmental
economics.

00:08:55.360 --> 00:08:59.430
And since I'm an environmental economist,
I always bet on Marty.

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:02.200
Harvard runs a betting pool every year for
the Nobel Prize.

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:04.690
So, I lost five dollars last year, because
he didn't win.

00:09:04.690 --> 00:09:09.130
But he did kind of pioneering work on this
idea that I'll come back and chat about a

00:09:09.130 --> 00:09:13.580
little more later on.
So, I do call myself "The World's First and

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:17.270
Only Stand-up Economist."
I really only have one thing going for me

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:20.590
and that's low expectations. [Laughter]
Actually, that's not true.

00:09:20.590 --> 00:09:24.430
I have one other thing going for me -- I get
to make fun of macroeconomists.

00:09:24.430 --> 00:09:27.630
You know, I'm a real economist, because I
can make fun of sub-disciplines that are totally

00:09:27.630 --> 00:09:31.500
indistinguishable to people on the outside.
You know, like people in Washington State

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:33.180
 -- where I live -- make fun of people in
Oregon.

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:38.070
People in Alabama make fun of people in Mississippi.
People in prison make fun of people in graduate

00:09:38.070 --> 00:09:43.490
school. [laughter]
I did go through five years of graduate school.

00:09:43.490 --> 00:09:47.930
I got my Ph.D. in economics only to decide
that I wanted to do stand-up comedy.

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:51.330
You can imagine how much this thrilled my
father.

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.880
He told me I'd never make it as a stand-up
economist, and I said, "Why not?"

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:59.880
And he said, "There's no demand." [laughter]
First joke I ever told on stage.

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:04.510
I said, "Don't worry about it. I'm a supply-side
economist." [laughter]

00:10:04.510 --> 00:10:06.360
I just stand up and let the jokes trickle
down.

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:13.920
I believe in the Laffer Curve.
You can also tell I'm a real economist, because

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:17.320
I can translate plain English into incomprehensible
gibberish.

00:10:17.320 --> 00:10:20.440
But briefly, while I was in graduate school,
I had the opposite ability -- I could translate

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:23.230
economic gibberish into plain English.
And that's where this next bit I want to do

00:10:23.230 --> 00:10:25.250
for you comes from.
I think some of you may have seen this on

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:28.290
YouTube.
If you have, don't worry -- there's new stuff

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:30.500
coming -- but, this is Mankiw's Principles
of Economics.

00:10:30.500 --> 00:10:34.380
So Greg Mankiw, a Harvard professor, chair
of the Counsel of Economic Advisors for President

00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:39.959
Bush for a couple of years -- which, I'm guessing,
is probably not at the top of his resumé.

00:10:39.959 --> 00:10:41.830
Also wrote the best-selling economics textbook
in the country.

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:45.170
It's based on these ten principles.
I know the font is small, but I generally

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:48.080
tell people not to bother reading these.
Just take my word that you pretty much need

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:52.331
a Ph.D. in economics to understand them.
Fortunately, I have one.

00:10:52.331 --> 00:10:57.149
So, I've taken it upon myself to translate
these principles for the more fortunate.

00:10:57.149 --> 00:11:01.240
We're going to begin by separating them into
the first seven principles, which are microeconomics,

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:04.870
and the last three, which are macroeconomics
 -- the difference of course being that microeconomists

00:11:04.870 --> 00:11:10.660
are wrong about specific things and macroeconomists
are wrong about things in general. [laughter]

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:14.180
Beginning with the macroprinciples -- eight,
nine, and ten -- these all have the exact

00:11:14.180 --> 00:11:18.550
same translation, namely "Blah, blah, blah."
[laughter]

00:11:18.550 --> 00:11:22.779
As proof I need only remind you that macroeconomists
have successfully predicted nine out of the

00:11:22.779 --> 00:11:30.170
last five recessions. [laughter]
And it's further proof we can now go up one

00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:33.649
font size.
So, let's go back to the microprinciples.

00:11:33.649 --> 00:11:36.730
The first one -- People Face Trade-offs.
The translation here is easy, "Choices are

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:40.080
bad."
This is a simple syllogism -- trade-offs are

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:42.460
bad.
Any time you have choices, you have trade-offs,

00:11:42.460 --> 00:11:45.779
therefore choices have to be bad.
As evidence that I'm actually driving the

00:11:45.779 --> 00:11:50.280
research literature in economics, here's a
paper that came out in 2008 called, "Why Fewer

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:56.671
Options may be Better." No duh.
If you don't understand why choices are bad

00:11:56.671 --> 00:11:59.230
though, take a look at the second principle
 -- "The Cost of Something is What You Give

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:02.380
Up to Get It."
Translation: "Choices are Really Bad."

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:03.921
Now, I have a simple demonstration of this
fact.

00:12:03.921 --> 00:12:08.501
Let's say that somebody offers you a Snickers
bar, all right -- that you value at a dollar.

00:12:08.501 --> 00:12:10.840
All right?
Then what you are loosely going to think of

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:14.709
as your economic profit in this situation
is the dollar of this Snickers bar minus the

00:12:14.709 --> 00:12:16.899
cost of what you go up to get it, which is
nothing.

00:12:16.899 --> 00:12:23.220
Your economic profit is a dollar.
Thanks, Google. [laughter]

00:12:23.220 --> 00:12:28.500
Now, to begin to see why choices are bad.
Imagine someone offers you a choice between

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:31.750
the Snickers bar that you value at a dollar,
right? -- and some M&amp;Ms that you value at

00:12:31.750 --> 00:12:36.960
70 cents.
Okay, now your economic profit is only 30

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:42.200
cents.
You begin to understand why choices are bad.

00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:45.880
The worst possible situation, in fact, is
being offered a choice between a Snickers

00:12:45.880 --> 00:12:52.670
bar and an identical Snickers bar. [laughter]
Now, people who are not trained in economics

00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:56.149
might think that that's no different than
just being offered one Snickers bar, but that

00:12:56.149 --> 00:13:02.790
kind of sloppy thinking will never get you
a tenure-track position. [laughter]

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:06.279
Summarizing then: Choices are bad. Choices
are really bad.

00:13:06.279 --> 00:13:08.310
I'm not going to beat around the bush with
you people.

00:13:08.310 --> 00:13:12.720
If you don't understand why choices are bad,
you're probably stupid. [chuckles]

00:13:12.720 --> 00:13:16.291
Moving on. Principle Number 3 -- rational
People Think of the Margin.

00:13:16.291 --> 00:13:22.670
Translation: People are stupid. [laughter]
It is immediately obvious to the most casual

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:26.110
observer with the meanest intelligence that
people do not think of the margin.

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:29.180
Nobody goes to the grocery store and says,
"I'm going to buy an orange.

00:13:29.180 --> 00:13:33.209
I'm going to buy another orange. I'm going
to buy another orange."

00:13:33.209 --> 00:13:36.610
That joke only makes sense to economists.
[laughter]

00:13:36.610 --> 00:13:40.329
People don't think like that, all right?
But if people don't think of the margin -- and

00:13:40.329 --> 00:13:44.959
if, as Mankiw says, "Rational people DO think
of the margin" -- we are led to a most unhappy

00:13:44.959 --> 00:13:49.240
conclusion, "People are not rational."
People, in other words, are stupid.

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:52.620
But before you despair for humanity, take
a look at the next principle -- People Respond

00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:55.400
to Incentives.
Now, the dictionary says that 'incentive'

00:13:55.400 --> 00:13:57.810
is a noun.
That means "Something that influences to action.

00:13:57.810 --> 00:14:00.710
Synonym: motive."
So when Mankiw says that people respond to

00:14:00.710 --> 00:14:06.760
incentives, what he's saying is that people
are motivated by motives.

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:11.100
You might think this is a bit like saying
that "Tautologies are tautological," right?

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:16.240
I mean, people would have to be pretty stupid
to be unmotivated by motives.

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:21.649
But remember, Principle 3 -- [laughter] -- People
are Stupid.

00:14:21.649 --> 00:14:26.519
Hence, the need for Principle 4 to tell us
that People Aren't That Stupid. [laughter]

00:14:26.519 --> 00:14:29.350
Summarizing again -- we move on to every economist's
favorite topic -- free trade.

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:31.151
Principle 5 -- trade can make everyone better
off.

00:14:31.151 --> 00:14:33.810
Translation: Trade can make everyone worse
off.

00:14:33.810 --> 00:14:37.640
You may wonder how the translation of Principle
5 is the opposite of the principle itself.

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:39.760
I have a simple proof of this fact that will
blow your mind.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:43.800
Here we go. I want you to compare two statements.
One of them is, "Trade can make everyone better

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:47.110
off" and the other one is "Trade will make
everyone better off."

00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:52.440
Now, if you had to pick one of those two statements
to put in your best-selling economics textbook,

00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:55.630
right?
It's no contest. The second statement is clearly

00:14:55.630 --> 00:14:59.920
better.
But Mankiw uses the first statement instead.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:05.410
And if you think about "Why?" there's only
one possible explanation.

00:15:05.410 --> 00:15:09.140
The second statement has got to be wrong.
[laughter]

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:12.460
In other words, trade can make some people
worse off, and from there, it's just a hop,

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:14.820
skip, and a jump to "Trade can make everyone
worse off." [laughter]

00:15:14.820 --> 00:15:19.420
I figured some of you had some questions about
this, so I added a footnote with some details

00:15:19.420 --> 00:15:26.209
 -- eat your heart out. [laughter]
Now that we've cleared that up, I want you

00:15:26.209 --> 00:15:30.740
to see the last two principles follow immediately
from Principle 5 in its translation, right?

00:15:30.740 --> 00:15:32.870
Markets are usually a good way to organize
economic activity.

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:36.850
In other words, Governments are Stupid.
Governments can sometimes improve market outcomes.

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:40.610
Governments aren't that stupid.
Follow immediately from five in its translation,

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:43.680
if trade can make everyone better off, then
what the heck do we need government for? Just

00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:46.950
let people trade, right?
But, if trade can make everyone worse off,

00:15:46.950 --> 00:15:51.029
we better have a government around to stop
people from trading, right?

00:15:51.029 --> 00:15:53.740
So there are the ten principles of economics
translated.

00:15:53.740 --> 00:15:58.501
And what I want you to notice here is how
subtle economics is, all right?

00:15:58.501 --> 00:16:01.430
Like, "People are stupid, but they're not
that stupid."

00:16:01.430 --> 00:16:03.630
"Governments are stupid, but they're not that
stupid."

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:07.380
The only thing that's not subtle in economics
is that "Choices are always really, really

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:11.570
bad."
So, I filmed this at a science convention

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:16.370
and put it up on my website, standupeconomist.com
 -- and also on YouTube -- a couple years

00:16:16.370 --> 00:16:22.540
ago, not thinking very much of it.
And I'm a little embarrassed to say that it's

00:16:22.540 --> 00:16:28.000
heading for a million hits on YouTube -- [whistling
 &amp; applause] -- which is a lot for economics

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.779
jokes, okay? [laughter]
Not a lot for videos about like, puppies,

00:16:32.779 --> 00:16:35.829
but it's a lot for economics jokes.
