00:18:47.419 --> 00:18:54.640
So, if any of you have economics-related funny
papers, then send them my way.

00:18:54.640 --> 00:18:58.640
I tend to get things from folks who have funny
economics papers, or -- more often -- people

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:03.620
who think that they have funny economics papers.
Tell you about some more recent developments

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:06.780
in the world of economics comedy.
This paper called "Japan's Phillips Curve,"

00:19:06.780 --> 00:19:09.730
looks like Japan.
So, if you need a refresher on the Phillips

00:19:09.730 --> 00:19:13.090
Curve, it's this idea that came out in the
50s and 60s that there's a trade-off between

00:19:13.090 --> 00:19:16.460
inflation and unemployment.
You can have high inflation, low unemployment,

00:19:16.460 --> 00:19:18.790
or vice versa.
But somewhere, you're always along that Phillips

00:19:18.790 --> 00:19:22.140
Curve line, right?
And then, the 70s and 80s, we had stagflation

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:26.110
 -- high inflation, also high unemployment.
Robert Lucas developed the Theory of Rational

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.500
Expectations.
Economists realized it was more complicated

00:19:28.500 --> 00:19:32.340
 -- everywhere, except in Japan.
So this paper was named the Funniest Economics

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:35.150
Paper of 2008.
There was considerable competition for that.

00:19:35.150 --> 00:19:41.130
And it was written by a Canadian, Gregor Smith.
And one of the great things about this paper

00:19:41.130 --> 00:19:43.650
is, it's linked from his website.
And the link on his website says that the

00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:53.440
"title of the paper is also the abstract,
and frankly, most of the text." [laughter]

00:19:53.440 --> 00:19:57.370
 -- which is pretty much what we should be
aiming for in all academic papers, I think.

00:19:57.370 --> 00:20:04.260
The rest of the paper is taken up by this
graph here. [laughter]

00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:09.420
So, on the x-axis, we have the unemployment
rate in Japan between 1980 and 2005.

00:20:09.420 --> 00:20:13.340
On the y-axis, we have the inflation rate.
For ease of viewing, the author rotates this

00:20:13.340 --> 00:20:22.400
around the y-axis, right?
And then, there's a map of Japan. [laughter]

00:20:22.400 --> 00:20:28.570
Extremely impressive research. [laughter]
Tell you a little bit of my own research in

00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:30.990
economics humor.
So first of all, this paper is called "Incentive

00:20:30.990 --> 00:20:33.740
Compatibility in the Hospital."
So this is an example of what's called a "pain

00:20:33.740 --> 00:20:36.820
scale."
This is an actual thing that doctors and nurses

00:20:36.820 --> 00:20:39.520
use to communicate with patients -- like,
if they don't share a common language, at

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:41.450
least you can point and indicate how much
pain you're in.

00:20:41.450 --> 00:20:45.920
So, in the US, health care accounts for about
16 percent of GDP.

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:51.460
That hurts a whole lot. [laughter]
It's roughly like one-and-a-half to two times

00:20:51.460 --> 00:20:53.700
more than most other rich countries pay for
health care.

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:57.510
And compounding the problem is that a lot
of those resources are wasted because of things

00:20:57.510 --> 00:21:00.669
that health economists study like "adverse
selection" or "moral hazard."

00:21:00.669 --> 00:21:05.990
Or the particular issue that I'm going to
focus on today is with patients who are malingering.

00:21:05.990 --> 00:21:11.050
So malingering is an actual medical phenomenon.
Stereotypically, somebody who's lonely -- they'll

00:21:11.050 --> 00:21:14.240
just go to the hospital and complain of low
back pain just so someone will pay attention

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:16.919
to them.
And this happens enough that medical professionals

00:21:16.919 --> 00:21:20.120
have tests for malingering.
So there's what's called the Axial Load Test.

00:21:20.120 --> 00:21:23.170
So if you complain of low back pain, they
might push down on your head like this and

00:21:23.170 --> 00:21:25.120
ask you if the pain is getting worse, all
right?

00:21:25.120 --> 00:21:28.630
If you go, "Ow, ow, ow, ow!" then they know
that you're faking it, okay?

00:21:28.630 --> 00:21:32.770
Physiologically, it's now possible to have
enhanced low back pain as a result of that

00:21:32.770 --> 00:21:35.530
axial load.
But my question is, why can't we just use

00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:38.710
economic incentives instead, what economists
call "incentive compatibility"?

00:21:38.710 --> 00:21:42.880
So my modest proposal is that, instead of
asking people this question, "How much does

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:45.690
the pain hurt?"
Instead, we should just ask them, "How much

00:21:45.690 --> 00:21:48.510
would you be willing to pay to make the pain
go away?" [laughter]

00:21:48.510 --> 00:21:57.970
And then, you just pick a bubble.
And so, macroeconomics -- I mentioned Robert

00:21:57.970 --> 00:22:01.169
Lucas a few minutes ago.
He won the Nobel Prize for his work on Rational

00:22:01.169 --> 00:22:05.580
Expectations.
So, I have what I modestly call "The Lucas-Bauman

00:22:05.580 --> 00:22:07.681
Hypothesis."
Modestly, because I could have called it "The

00:22:07.681 --> 00:22:11.020
Bauman-Lucas Hypothesis."
Let me show you what it says graphically.

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:15.020
If we look at the amount of knowledge that
we have about macroeconomics, that we've gained

00:22:15.020 --> 00:22:18.400
over the last 150 years, right?
It's been a steady upward trend.

00:22:18.400 --> 00:22:25.160
But if we look at our level of understanding
of the macroeconomy, [laughter], it's been

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:28.330
flat.
The Lucas-Bauman Hypothesis explains why.

00:22:28.330 --> 00:22:32.390
The answer, of course, being that "Advances
in macroeconomics produce complexities in

00:22:32.390 --> 00:22:38.280
the macroeconomy" -- think like credit-default
swaps -- that offset the theoretical advances.

00:22:38.280 --> 00:22:41.299
Or in very simple layperson's terms, Macroeconomics
is Pointless.

00:22:41.299 --> 00:22:48.030
[laughter] Finally, some more economics of
global warming.

00:22:48.030 --> 00:22:51.000
So this is what I work on when I'm being an
academic.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.281
So I'll tell some jokes, then I'll tell a
little bit of serious stuff.

00:22:53.281 --> 00:22:55.000
Then, I'll go back and tell some more jokes
at the end.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.311
So, there are a bunch of economists who work
on climate change.

00:22:57.311 --> 00:23:01.110
I'm one of them.
And there are folks who also do like cost-benefit

00:23:01.110 --> 00:23:04.860
analysis modeling of climate change.
The most famous model is Bill Nordhaus' model.

00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:09.080
At Yale, it's called the "DICE" model -- the
"Dynamic Integrated Model of Climate and the

00:23:09.080 --> 00:23:11.610
Economy."
A few years ago, he came up with a regional

00:23:11.610 --> 00:23:16.039
version of this model.
That is, of course, called the "RICE" model.

00:23:16.039 --> 00:23:21.250
For obvious reasons, there is no local version
of this model. [laughter]

00:23:21.250 --> 00:23:24.770
I have my own model of climate and the economy.
It's called "The Value-laden, Assumption-laden,

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:29.299
Nicely Linear Approximation, Integrated model
of Climate and the Economy" or the "Vanilla

00:23:29.299 --> 00:23:34.780
Ice" model. [laughter]
The Vanilla Ice Model has some theory; it

00:23:34.780 --> 00:23:37.140
has some policy.
So, the theory actually goes back to this

00:23:37.140 --> 00:23:39.870
footnote here, right?
-- about trade making everyone worse off.

00:23:39.870 --> 00:23:43.841
And it's actually true in a very "made-up
economics model" sort of way that you can

00:23:43.841 --> 00:23:46.039
have a situation where trade makes everyone
worse off.

00:23:46.039 --> 00:23:48.919
And since this is related to climate change,
I'm just going to talk you through this for

00:23:48.919 --> 00:23:51.300
a minute.
So, imagine we live in a small town, right?

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:53.990
Small town has just three people in it -- Orange,
Pink, and Blue.

00:23:53.990 --> 00:23:57.390
They all live in this town.
Town has an air pollution problem, and they're

00:23:57.390 --> 00:24:00.710
all good Americans, so they each have a garage
full of stuff that they don't use. All right?

00:24:00.710 --> 00:24:04.390
So now, we're going to see some trades.
So first, Orange is going to sell a lawnmower

00:24:04.390 --> 00:24:07.730
 -- let's say -- to Pink. All right?
They both get a hundred dollars in value from

00:24:07.730 --> 00:24:09.991
the trade.
Orange sells the lawnmower for a hundred dollars

00:24:09.991 --> 00:24:13.640
that was just sitting in her garage.
Pink values the lawn mower at $200.

00:24:13.640 --> 00:24:17.179
She only has to pay a hundred for it.
So she gets a hundred dollars in net benefits.

00:24:17.179 --> 00:24:21.020
The problem is that, when Pink starts using
the lawn mower that was just sitting in Orange's

00:24:21.020 --> 00:24:24.900
garage, all right? -- you get a little bit
of air pollution in the town.

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:26.980
And again, this is a made-up economics model,
right?

00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:31.741
So maybe there's health impacts that we can
monetize at like $80 per person. All right?

00:24:31.741 --> 00:24:33.600
Not just for Orange and Pink, but also for
Blue.

00:24:33.600 --> 00:24:36.169
All right -- the negative externality in this
case.

00:24:36.169 --> 00:24:39.530
So note that Orange and Pink are going to
continue to make the trade, because they each

00:24:39.530 --> 00:24:42.820
get $20 in net benefits.
So, now we'll see another trade.

00:24:42.820 --> 00:24:46.870
Pink sells something to Blue -- a snowblower.
They each get a hundred dollars in value from

00:24:46.870 --> 00:24:50.320
the trade -- Pink from selling the snowblower
for a hundred dollars, Blue values it at 200,

00:24:50.320 --> 00:24:54.230
she only has to pay a hundred, right?
But when Blue starts using the snowblower

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:57.530
that was just sitting in Pink's garage, air
pollution gets worse.

00:24:57.530 --> 00:25:00.630
Maybe an additional $80 in health care costs
for everybody.

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:03.970
And now, we can just complete the circle.
Blue sells a leaf blower to Orange.

00:25:03.970 --> 00:25:07.450
They get a hundred dollars in benefits.
Air pollution gets worse -- an additional

00:25:07.450 --> 00:25:11.520
$80 in health care costs for everyone.
And now, if you add up any one of these columns,

00:25:11.520 --> 00:25:16.210
you see that the sum of all three of those
trades together leaves everybody at minus

00:25:16.210 --> 00:25:19.350
40.
So, this is the tragedy of the commons, the

00:25:19.350 --> 00:25:22.981
prisoner's dilemma.
And the economic idea here is that each of

00:25:22.981 --> 00:25:26.350
those people's trades are individually rational.
If you ask them if they want to take back

00:25:26.350 --> 00:25:28.820
any of the trades that they engaged in, they'll
say "No." All right?

00:25:28.820 --> 00:25:32.850
Because they get $20 in net benefits each
for each trade that they are engaged in.

00:25:32.850 --> 00:25:34.900
But altogether, the trades end up hurting
everyone.

00:25:34.900 --> 00:25:38.440
If you want to belabor the point and make
a connection to climate change, we could -- I

00:25:38.440 --> 00:25:41.860
don't know -- like label the people or something.
[laughter]

00:25:41.860 --> 00:25:46.059
So this is kind of the economic model -- a
very simple model -- the way that economists

00:25:46.059 --> 00:25:49.020
think about climate change.
I'll mention a couple of things about climate

00:25:49.020 --> 00:25:50.590
change.
So, I'm not a climate scientist, but I do

00:25:50.590 --> 00:25:53.520
hang out with climate scientists at the University
of Washington and elsewhere.

00:25:53.520 --> 00:25:56.940
So one thing to note is, carbon emissions
are going up.

00:25:56.940 --> 00:26:02.160
People are very good at burning fossil fuels.
Projected at double roughly between 1990 and

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:04.190
2030.
And a lot of that growth is coming in the

00:26:04.190 --> 00:26:07.850
developing world, all right?
So the red and the green here are the U.S.

00:26:07.850 --> 00:26:11.610
and the rest of the rich world.
The purple is China and the yellow is the

00:26:11.610 --> 00:26:16.809
rest of the developing world.
So very rapid projections for increasing CO2

00:26:16.809 --> 00:26:20.440
emissions, especially in the developing part
of the world.

00:26:20.440 --> 00:26:23.240
Second thing you need to know is just the
basics of the greenhouse effect.

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:25.270
So you probably learned this from Al Gore,
right?

00:26:25.270 --> 00:26:28.720
But the idea is that you got energy in from
the sun and then some of that energy gets

00:26:28.720 --> 00:26:32.730
radiated back out into space.
And greenhouse gases are this blanket of heat

00:26:32.730 --> 00:26:37.789
trapping gases that partially reflect some
of that outgoing radiation back to the earth.

00:26:37.789 --> 00:26:39.800
This is not controversial among scientists
anyway.

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:43.580
And one of the first people to work on this
was this fellow, Arrhenius, who was a chemist

00:26:43.580 --> 00:26:47.620
in Sweden in 1896.
He did the first estimate of what would temperatures

00:26:47.620 --> 00:26:51.740
 -- by how much temperatures would go up if
we doubled CO2 in the atmosphere.

00:26:51.740 --> 00:26:56.750
And his point estimate is still in the range
that climate scientists talk about today.

00:26:56.750 --> 00:27:00.480
One big difference between where he was and
where we are now is that, he thought climate

00:27:00.480 --> 00:27:06.820
change was going to be awesome, because he
lived in Sweden. [laughter] In 1896.

00:27:06.820 --> 00:27:11.380
And we think it's a little -- probably going
to be a little less awesome these days.

00:27:11.380 --> 00:27:14.770
And here's temperature trends.
So, you may see a lot of stuff in the media

00:27:14.770 --> 00:27:18.090
about what's going on with temperatures.
And temperatures bounce around a lot, but

00:27:18.090 --> 00:27:22.210
they're going up pretty much just like the
climate scientists projected -- by about .2,

00:27:22.210 --> 00:27:26.650
.15 degrees centigrade per decade, and that's
projected to continue for the next couple

00:27:26.650 --> 00:27:29.500
of decades.
Now, if you don't believe in climate change,

00:27:29.500 --> 00:27:32.840
that's okay.
I'll find common ground with you anyway.

00:27:32.840 --> 00:27:36.120
But, it's worth just keeping an eye on the
temperature projections.

00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:39.340
One of the cool things about science is, they
make testable predictions, right?

00:27:39.340 --> 00:27:42.690
And so, if you don't believe in climate change,
you just kind of wait five or ten years, and

00:27:42.690 --> 00:27:47.870
then see what happens.
So, the economics of climate change -- which

00:27:47.870 --> 00:27:51.640
I work on -- is pretty simple.
It's based -- that's the policy part of the

00:27:51.640 --> 00:27:55.450
Vanilla Ice model -- and the policy part is
based on a simple idea, right -- which is

00:27:55.450 --> 00:27:59.100
that, the way to get less pollution is to
make polluting expensive.

00:27:59.100 --> 00:28:02.200
And you can do that sort of.
Economists talk about two flavors of that

00:28:02.200 --> 00:28:06.730
 -- one of them is like a carbon tax, the
other is an auction 'Cap and Trade' system.

00:28:06.730 --> 00:28:10.730
We tend to think that they're pretty similar,
more similar than they are different.

00:28:10.730 --> 00:28:15.419
And in both cases, the goal of those policies
is to raise the price of fossil fuels so that

00:28:15.419 --> 00:28:20.090
you get capitalism and free market economics
and stuff working to develop alternatives

00:28:20.090 --> 00:28:27.240
to promote conservation -- all that great
stuff that's the power of free enterprise.

00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:32.200
And trying to get that to work for the environment.
So what I work on as a economist is, How do

00:28:32.200 --> 00:28:36.520
we use the tools of economics to protect the
environment?

00:28:36.520 --> 00:28:42.950
Fossil fuel prices are going to go up.
And lots of folks would like to get - they'd

00:28:42.950 --> 00:28:46.779
like to get all that innovation and clean
energy and stuff without fossil fuel prices

00:28:46.779 --> 00:28:49.320
going up.
And I happen to think that that's going to

00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:51.990
be real hard.
I think you're going to need the price stable

00:28:51.990 --> 00:28:54.049
to make that happen.
There's a little bit of good news.

00:28:54.049 --> 00:28:57.549
And the good news is that, with either of
these systems -- with a carbon tax or with

00:28:57.549 --> 00:29:00.429
auction Cap and Trade -- you get a pile of
money.

00:29:00.429 --> 00:29:02.520
And you can do great stuff with that pile
of money.

00:29:02.520 --> 00:29:07.960
You probably have your own ideas about spending
it on mass transit or clean energy research

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:11.370
or whatever.
What I talk to folks about is the idea of

00:29:11.370 --> 00:29:16.200
using it to reduce or eliminate existing taxes.
So environmental tax reform -- revenue-neutral

00:29:16.200 --> 00:29:19.840
tax shift -- or some of the names that folks
talk about. All right?

00:29:19.840 --> 00:29:23.550
And the underlying idea here is that, for
economists, the way that you should organize

00:29:23.550 --> 00:29:27.730
a tax system is, you should start by taxing
things that you want less of, instead of taxing

00:29:27.730 --> 00:29:31.770
things that you want more of. All right?
So right now we tax employment, we tax savings,

00:29:31.770 --> 00:29:33.770
we tax investment.
Those are all things that we'd like to have

00:29:33.770 --> 00:29:36.640
more of.
So we shouldn't be discouraging them.

00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:42.450
So we should get rid of some of those taxes,
and instead have taxes on carbon emissions

00:29:42.450 --> 00:29:46.309
and things that we want less of.
So the underlying vision here that I go around

00:29:46.309 --> 00:29:51.080
and talk to folks about is that we could be
replacing part of our tax code with carbon

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:52.809
pricing.
And there's actually a great model for this

00:29:52.809 --> 00:29:56.840
north of where I am in Seattle in the province
of British Columbia. They did this.

00:29:56.840 --> 00:30:03.419
There was -- the premier there, actually from
a right-of-center party, implemented a $30

00:30:03.419 --> 00:30:07.350
per ton of CO2 carbon tax.
So that's like 30 cents a gallon of gasoline.

00:30:07.350 --> 00:30:10.289
So that's not nothing.
And then, use the money -- a hundred percent

00:30:10.289 --> 00:30:14.790
of the money went to rebate personal and corporate
income taxes at the provincial level in a

00:30:14.790 --> 00:30:19.409
way that sort of offset impacts on low-income
households.

00:30:19.409 --> 00:30:22.330
And a super great policy.
So I'm working with some folks in Washington

00:30:22.330 --> 00:30:25.110
State to probably run a ballot measure or
something there.

00:30:25.110 --> 00:30:28.860
I can always dream to make that happen in
Washington.

00:30:28.860 --> 00:30:32.940
And it's something that you could do here
in California also, right?

00:30:32.940 --> 00:30:37.429
And it would be a great thing for all sorts
of reasons. Even if you don't believe in climate

00:30:37.429 --> 00:30:41.950
change, there are national security reasons,
right? -- for wanting to reduce the dependence

00:30:41.950 --> 00:30:48.870
on foreign oil, the market price of oil.
And probably the best story I have about this

00:30:48.870 --> 00:30:51.039
